What is the output of the following Java program?
class Test   
{  
    public static void main (String args[])   
    {  
        for(int i=0; 0; i++)   
        {  
            System.out.println("Hello Tpointtech");  
        }  
    }  
}  
The above code will result in a compilation error due to the 
non-boolean expression in the second part of the for loop, and given is an integer value, i.e., 0.
---
Structure of for loop:
for(initialization; condition; increment)
So here:
Initialization → int i = 0 ✅
Condition → 0 ❌
Increment → i++ ✅
-------
Correct Version (If You Want Infinite Loop)
for(int i = 0; true; i++) {
    System.out.println("Hello Tpointtech");
}


OR

for(;;) {
    System.out.println("Hello Tpointtech");
}


Both create infinite loops.
